                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/2700</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-09-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 3, 1917</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">memorandum</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The Japanese Embassy in London has communicated to His Majesty’s Principal
                    Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs a memorandum concerning the internal
                    situation in China. The memorandum advocates the support of the Central
                    Government and the withholding of encouragement or material assistance from its
                    opponents.</p>
                <p>His Majesty’s Government being convinced that the adoption by all the Allied
                    Powers of a policy based on these lines affords the best prospect of the
                    restoration of order in China have communicated to the Japanese Ambassador in
                    London their readiness to adhere to the policy outlined in his memorandum.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
